@ChAnTAxR If you think that the 'hero's journey' means you get the same story every time, you don't understand what the concept of the hero's journey refers to. It does not dictate that specific things should happen, it just states that (main) characters should grow and learn and change throughout the story and overcome certain obstacles. A story without that is almost always bad, because character growth is what makes characters interesting.

And about escapism, I find that in Lord of the Rings, but also in A Song of Ice and Fire. It does not mean a lack of moral complexity, you're simply wrong about that. It means escaping to another universe, away from our boring daily lives, and have the feeling to be transported to another reality. What that other reality is, is irrelevant outside of the one condition that it is different enough from our own reality that we can forget that for a while.
And what ruins escapism is therefore not moral complexity, it's elements in the story that try to remind us of the real world. Like real world politics, or characters acting or speaking in ways that only make sense in the current real-world context.

@frankvandorp9732 Many story structures also do the same things, but the difference is that the hero's journey's "checkpoints" are much more frequently easier to spot, and trying to subvert it leads to a completely new story structure.

But moral complexity does remind us of the real world, which was my point. Only in a fictional world would someone be pure evil, or "really good with one flaw that gets fixed in the most obvious way possible"

People don't like thinking about how their enemies have entire lives, which is exactly what moral simplicity does

@ChAnTAxR "But moral complexity does remind us of the real world"
Speak for yourself. I'm very well capable of enjoying moral complexity without being reminded of the real world, which is exactly why it doesn't hinder my escapism.

As for the hero's journey, you still persist in a very simplistic view of the concept, as if they're fixed predictable "checkpoints". That's not how the hero's journey works, at all.

